The '''China Fusion Engineering Test Reactor (CFETR)''' is a proposed [[tokamak]] [[nuclear fusion]] [[nuclear fusion reactor|reactor]] in China.<ref name=iaea>{{cite journal|last1=Liu|first1=Xiaogang|last2=Wang|first2=Zhaoliang|last3=Ren|first3=Yong|last4=Li|first4=Junjun|last5=Yin|first5=Dapeng|last6=Li|first6=Lei|last7=Gao|first7=Xiang|last8=Wu|first8=Yu|title=Mechanical performance evaluation of the CFETR central solenoid model coil design|journal=Nuclear Fusion|date=1 January 2018|volume=58|issue=1|pages=016035|doi=10.1088/1741-4326/aa9866}}</ref> CFETR construction is planned for the 2020s as a demonstration of the feasibility of large scale fusion power generation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Li|first1=Jiangang|title=Closing gaps to CFETR Readiness|url=http://www-naweb.iaea.org/napc/physics/meetings/TM49530/website/talks/May%2012%20Sessions/Li_J.pdf|publisher=Institute of Plasma Physics, CAS|accessdate=30 May 2018|location=IAEA TCM 3rd DEMO workshop, Hefei, China|date=May 11-14, 2015}}</ref> The project would include two phases of operation. The first phase aims to demonstrate steady-state operation and [[tritium]] breeding. The second phase would include an update of the system to obtain fusion power production of 1 GW and a [[fusion gain]] higher than 12, with tritium self-sufficiency.<ref name=iaea />
