Sunfire, a [[clean technology]] company, operates a pilot plant in [[Dresden, Germany]]. The current process involves [[high-temperature electrolysis]] powered by electricity generated from [[renewable energy]] sources to split water into [[hydrogen]] and [[oxygen]]. The next two chemical processes to create a liquid [[energy carrier]] called blue crude are done at a temperature of {{Convert|220|C}} and a pressure of {{Convert|25|bar}}. In a conversion step, hydrogen and carbon dioxide are used to create [[syngas]] with water as byproduct. The syngas, which contains [[carbon monoxide]] and hydrogen, reacts to generate the blue crude.
* Sunfire power-to-liquids system: Base products are carbon dioxide (CO<sub>2</sub>) and water (H<sub>2</sub>O)<ref>{{cite web|title=Fuels from solar energy, CO2 and water|url=http://www.sunfire.de/en/produkte/fuel/power-to-liquids|website=sunfire.de|publisher=Sunfire GmbH|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>
:1st step: Electrolysis of Water ([[Solid oxide electrolyser cell|SOEC]]) −water is split into hydrogen and oxygen.
:2nd step: Conversion Reactor ([[Water-gas shift reaction#Reverse water-gas shift|RWGSR]]) −hydrogen and carbon dioxide are inputs to the Conversion Reactor that outputs hydrogen, carbon monoxide, and water.
:3rd step: F-T Reactor −hydrogen and carbon monoxide are inputs<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ciferno|first1=Jared|last2=Marano|first2=John|title=Benchmarking Biomass Gasification Technologies for Fuels, Chemicals and Hydrogen Production|url=http://www.netl.doe.gov/File%20Library/research/coal/energy%20systems/gasification/BMassGasFinal.pdf|publisher=National Energy Technology Laboratory|accessdate=19 May 2015|date=June 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Syngas Optimized for Intended Products|url=http://www.netl.doe.gov/research/coal/energy-systems/gasification/gasifipedia/syngas-optimization|website=NETL - Gasification Introduction|publisher=U.S. DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref> to the F-T Reactor that outputs paraffinic and olefinic hydrocarbons, ranging from methane to high molecular weight waxes.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Sang-Eon Park|author2=Jong-San Chang|author3=Kyu-Wan Lee|title=Carbon Dioxide Utilization for Global Sustainability: Proceedings of the 7th International Conference on Carbon Dioxide Utilization, Seoul, Korea, October 12-16, 2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RX6kgpBaR_AC&pg=PA18|date=27 October 2004|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-08-047217-1|page=18|quote=Traditional Fischer-Tropsch synthesis using CO/H2 feedgas produces paraffinic and olefinic hydrocarbons, ranging from methane to high molecular weight waxes.}}</ref>

The final step is also known as [[Fischer–Tropsch process]] which was first developed in 1925 by German chemists Franz Fischer and Hans Tropsch. After the blue crude is produced, it can be refined to create e-diesel on site, saving the fuel and other infrastructure costs on crude transportation.<ref name=greencarcongress/><ref>{{cite web|title=German-made 'miracle' machine turns water into gasoline|url=http://rt.com/news/209619-sunfire-water-synthetic-fuel/|website=RT News|publisher=TV-Novosti|accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref> As of April 2015, Sunfire has a capability to produce a limited amount of fuel at {{Convert|160|litres}} a day. There is a plan to increase the production to an industrial scale.<ref>{{cite news|last1=MacDonald|first1=Fiona|title=Audi has successfully made diesel fuel from carbon dioxide and water|url=https://www.sciencealert.com/audi-have-successfully-made-diesel-fuel-from-air-and-water|accessdate=29 April 2015|work=Science Alert|date=27 April 2015}}</ref>

Audi also partners with a company named Climeworks which manufactures carbon dioxide capturing machines. Climeworks technologies can absorb atmospheric carbon dioxide which is chemically captured at the surface of a [[sorbent]] until it becomes saturated. At that point, the sorbent is introduced with {{Convert|95|°C}} heat in a [[desorption]] cycle to drive out the high-purity carbon dioxide that can be used during the conversion step of the blue crude generation process. The atmospheric carbon dioxide capturing process has 90% of energy demand in the form of low-temperature heat and the rest from electrical energy for pumping and control. The combined plant of Climeworks and Sunfire in Dresden became operational in November 2014.<ref name=greencarcongress>{{cite news|title=Audi in new e-fuels project: synthetic diesel from water, air-captured {{CO2}} and green electricity; "Blue Crude"|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2014/11/20141114-audibluecrude.html|accessdate=29 April 2015|work=Green Car Congress.|date=14 November 2014}}</ref> A plant on [[Herøya]] in Norway, producing 10 million liters per year, is being considered, as {{CO2}} from a fertilizer plant is readily available and electricity is relatively cheap in Norway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tu.no/artikler/norsk-selskap-kan-bli-forst-i-verden-til-a-produsere-audis-vidunderdiesel/348424|title=Norsk selskap kan bli først i verden til å produsere Audis «vidunderdiesel»|work=[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>

===Properties===
As much as eighty percent of blue crude can be converted into e-diesel. The fuel contains no [[sulfur]] or [[aromatics]], and has a high [[cetane number]]. These properties allow it to be blended with typical fossil diesel and used as a replacement fuel in automobiles with [[diesel engine]]s.<ref name=greencarcongress/>

===Oxygen by-product===
In future designs,<ref>{{cite web|title=HELMETH EU: A Project in the Amount of EUR 3.8 Million for More Efficient Methane Gas Production from Regenerative Power by Thermal Interlinkage of Chemical Processes|url=http://www.kit.edu/kit/english/pi_2014_14950.php|website=Karlsruhe Institute of Technology|publisher=Karlsruhe Institute of Technology|accessdate=21 May 2015|date=10 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Kondratenko, Evgenii V.|author2=Rodemerck, Uwe|title=A Dual-Reactor Concept for the High-Yielding Conversion of Methane into Higher Hydrocarbons|journal=ChemCatChem|date=9 January 2013|volume=5|issue=3|pages=697–700|doi=10.1002/cctc.201200779|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/cctc.201200779/full|publisher=WILEY-VCH Verlag}}</ref> the oxygen [[by-product]] may be combined with [[renewable natural gas]]<ref>[http://www.cedec.com/files/default/8-2014-05-27-cedec-gas-day-reinhard-otten-audi-ag.pdf The first industrial PtG plant – Audi e-gas as driver for the energy turnaround]</ref> in the [[oxidative coupling of methane]] to [[ethylene]]:<ref>{{cite journal| author=Zhang, Q. |year = 2003| title = Recent Progress in Direct Partial Oxidation of Methane to Methanol | journal =J. Natural Gas Chem.| volume = 12|pages = 81–89}}</ref><ref>Olah, G.,  Molnar, A. “Hydrocarbon Chemistry” John Wiley & Sons, New York, 2003. {{ISBN|978-0-471-41782-8}}.</ref>

: 2{{chem|CH|4}} + {{chem|O|2}} &rarr; {{chem|C|2|H|4}} + 2{{chem|H|2|O}}

The reaction is [[exothermic]] (∆H = -280 kJ/mol) and occurs at high temperatures (750–950 ˚C).<ref name="Lunsford">{{cite journal| author=Lunsford, J.H. |year = 1995| title = The catalytic coupling of methane | journal = Angew. Chem. Int. Ed. Engl.| volume = 34|pages = 970–980| doi= 10.1002/anie.199509701}}</ref> The yield of the desired {{chem|C|2}} products is reduced by non-selective reactions of [[methyl radical]]s with the reactor surface and oxygen, which produces carbon monoxide and carbon dioxide by-products. Another ethylene production initiative developed by the European Commission through the Seventh Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development is the OCMOL process, which is the Oxidative Coupling of Methane (OCM) and simultaneous Reforming of Methane (RM) in a fully  integrated reactor.<ref>[http://www.ocmol.eu/uploads/media/OCMOL_brochure.pdf OCMOL: Oxidative Coupling of Methane followed by Oligomerization to Liquids]</ref>

==Biocatalytic conversions==
[[File:Helioculture image.png|thumb|right|300px|Helioculture combines [[brackish water]] (or [[graywater]]), nutrients, photosynthetic organisms, carbon dioxide, and sunlight to create fuel.]]
Audi also partners with a United States company, Joule, to develop Joule's ''Sunflow-D'' as e-diesel for Audi. Joule's plant in [[New Mexico]] involves the use of [[genetically modified]] microorganisms in bright sunlight to act as a [[catalyst]] for the conversion of carbon dioxide and salty water into [[hydrocarbon]]s.<ref name=greencarcongress/><ref>{{cite web|title=A Transformative Production Platform for Liquid Fuel from the Sun|url=http://www.sae.org/events/gim/presentations/2013/glass_david.pdf|website=sae.org|publisher=Joule|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref> The process can be modified for longer molecular chains to produce [[alkane]]s in order to create synthetic diesel.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kacher|first1=Georg|title=CAR tech: Audi's miracle e-fuel (2013)|url=http://www.carmagazine.co.uk/car-news/industry-news/audi/car-tech-audis-miracle-e-fuel-2013/|accessdate=29 April 2015|work=Car Magazine|date=29 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Joule and Audi partner on sustainable liquid transportation fuels|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2012/09/joule-audi-20120917.html|accessdate=7 May 2015|work=Green Car Congress|date=17 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Audi e-diesel and e-ethanol|url=http://www.audi-technology-portal.de/en/mobility-for-the-future/audi-future-lab-mobility_en/audi-future-energies_en/audi-e-diesel-and-e-ethanol|publisher=Audi|accessdate=7 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Casey|first1=Tina|title=Buh-Bye, Corn Ethanol: Joule Makes The Same Thing From Recycled CO2|url=http://cleantechnica.com/2015/05/12/buh-bye-corn-ethanol-joule-makes-thing-recycled-co2/|website=CleanTechnica|publisher=Sustainable Enterprises Media, Inc.|accessdate=20 May 2015|date=May 12, 2015}}</ref>

[[Joule Unlimited]] is the first company to patent a modified organism that continuously secretes hydrocarbon fuel. The organism is a [[Cyanobacteria|single-celled cyanobacterium]], also known as blue-green algae, although it is technically not an algae. It produces the fuel using photosynthesis, the same process that [[Plant|multi-cellular green plants]] use, to make sugars and other materials from water, carbon dioxide, and sunlight.<ref>{{cite news|last1=WALD|first1=MATTHEW L.|title=Biotech Company to Patent Fuel-Secreting Bacterium|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/14/science/earth/14fuel.html|accessdate=6 May 2015|agency=NYTimes.com|issue=September 14, 2010, on page B2 of the New York edition|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=September 13, 2010}}</ref>

==Similar initiatives==
There are other initiatives to create synthetic fuel from carbon dioxide and water, however they are not part of Audi's initiatives and the fuels are not called e-diesel. The [[water splitting]] methods vary.
*[[Concentrated solar power]]
**2004 Sunshine-to-Petrol – [[Sandia National Laboratories]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sunshine to Petrol|url=http://energy.sandia.gov/energy/renewable-energy/solar-energy/sunshine-to-petrol/|website=Sandia National Laboratories|publisher=United States Department of Energy (DOE)|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://energy.sandia.gov/wp-content/gallery/uploads/S2P_SAND2009-5796P.pdf SNL: Sunshine to Petrol - Solar Recycling of Carbon Dioxide into Hydrocarbon Fuels]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sandia and Sunshine-to-Petrol™: Renewable Drop-in Transportation Fuels|url=https://www.fbo.gov/index?s=opportunity&mode=form&id=698e254d2c8fea2fc478add76d2aac1c&tab=core&_cview=0|website=Federal Business Opportunities|publisher=U.S. Federal Government|accessdate=15 May 2015|date=Oct 29, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Biello|first1=David|title=Reverse Combustion: Can CO2 Be Turned Back into Fuel?|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/turning-carbon-dioxide-back-into-fuel/|website=Scientific American - Energy & Sustainability|publisher=Scientific American, a Division of Nature America, Inc.|accessdate=17 May 2015|date=September 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lavelle|first1=Marianne|title=Carbon Recycling: Mining the Air for Fuel|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/energy/2011/08/110811-turning-carbon-emissions-into-fuel/|website=National Geographic - News|publisher=National Geographic Society|accessdate=19 May 2015|date=August 11, 2011}}</ref><ref>Onur Taylan and Halil Berberoglu (2013). Fuel Production Using Concentrated Solar Energy, Application of Solar Energy, Prof. Radu Rugescu (Ed.), {{ISBN|978-953-51-0969-3}}, InTech, DOI: 10.5772/54057. Available from: [http://www.intechopen.com/books/application-of-solar-energy/fuel-production-using-concentrated-solar-energy Intechopen.com]</ref>
**2013 NewCO2Fuels – New CO2 Fuels Ltd ([[ISO 3166-2:IL|IL]]) and [[Weizmann Institute of Science]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bright Way to Convert Greenhouse Gas to Biofuel|url=http://web.weizmann.org.uk/2012/12/18/bright-way-to-convert-greenhouse-gas-to-biofuel/|website=Weizmann UK|publisher=Weizmann UK. Registered Charity No. 232666|accessdate=19 May 2015|date=18 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CO2 and H2O Dissociation Process|url=http://www.newco2fuels.co.il/technology/1/process|website=NCF - Technology Process|publisher=New CO2 Fuels Ltd|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.newco2fuels.co.il/files/files/NCF%20Newsletter%20Issue01%20Sept%202012.pdf Newsletter NewCO2Fuels, Issue 1, September 2012]</ref><ref>[http://www.asx.com.au/asxpdf/20130411/pdf/42f6524n3tpxs3.pdf From challenge to opportunity New {{chem|C|O|2}} Fuels: An Introduction...]</ref>
**2014 Solar-Jet Fuels – Consortium partners [[ETH Zurich]], [[Royal Dutch Shell]], [[German Aerospace Center|DLR]], Bauhaus Luftfahrt, ARTTIC.<ref>{{cite web|title=SOLAR-JET Project|url=http://www.solar-jet.aero/page/about-solar-jet/objectives.php|website=SOLAR-JET|publisher=SOLAR-JET Project Office: ARTTIC|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sunlight to jet fuel|url=https://www.ethz.ch/en/news-and-events/eth-news/news/2014/04/sunlight-to-jet-fuel.html|website=The ETH Zurich|publisher=Eidgenössische Technische Hochschule Zürich|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Alexander|first1=Meg|title="Solar" jet fuel created from water and carbon dioxide|url=http://www.gizmag.com/sunlight-carbon-dioxide-jet-fuel/31872/|website=Gizmag|publisher=Gizmag|accessdate=15 May 2015|date=May 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SOLARJET demonstrates full process for thermochemical production of renewable jet fuel from H2O & CO2|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2015/04/20150428-solarjet.html|website=Green Car Congress|publisher=BioAge Group, LLC|accessdate=15 May 2015|date=28 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Aldo Steinfeld - Solar Syngas|url=https://b60099084-dev-blakely-dot-google-solveforx.appspot.com/moonshots/aldo-steinfeld-solar-syngas|website=Solve For <X>|publisher=Google Inc.}}</ref><ref>[http://www.psi.ch/lst/BooksEN/MRS_Bulletin_-_Energy_Quarterly,_Vol_38,_2013.pdf Brewing fuels in a solar furnace]</ref>
*[[High-temperature electrolysis]]
