{{Location map|United Kingdom|relief=1|lat=58.0|long=-0.3833|caption=Location in UK continental shelf, North Sea|float=right|background=white|width=200}}
'''Goldeneye Gas Platform''' is an unmanned and now abandoned offshore gas production [[oil platform|platform]] in [[North Sea]] block 14/29, in the South Halibut basin area of the outer [[Moray Firth]], 105&nbsp;km northeast of [[St Fergus Gas Plant]] in [[Scotland]]. The topsides were designed by SLP Engineering Ltd. Production was from five wells with well fluids separated by a single vertical separator vessel. Separated liquids were re-injected into the export gas stream without further treatment. Facilities were provided for the installation of a future produced water coalescer and flash drum.<ref>Process Flow Diagrams: Gas Production and Future Water Treatment </ref> Gas was piped ashore to St Fergus under well pressure, without using compressors, where it was processed. It operated in {{convert|120|m}} of water.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quadrant 14 |url=https://www.og.decc.gov.uk/web_files/quad_maps/maps/Q14.pdf |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130405084002/https://www.og.decc.gov.uk/web_files/quad_maps/maps/Q14.pdf |dead-url=yes |archive-date=5 April 2013 |work=UKCS Quadrant Map |publisher=Department of Energy and Climate Change |accessdate=5 June 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Goldeneye Gas Platform, United Kingdom|url=http://www.offshore-technology.com/projects/goldeneye/|work=Industry Projects|publisher=offshore-technology.com|accessdate=5 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Goldeneye takes flight|url=http://www.fwc.com/publications/tech_papers/files/Goldeneye.pdf|work=Process Engineering|accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> The field was discovered in 1996, production started in 2004. and the platform was abandoned in 2011. It has a potential use for [[Carbon capture and storage|carbon dioxide storage]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Goldeneye|url=http://www.subseaiq.com/data/PrintProject.aspx?project_id=309&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|work=Subsea IQ|publisher=Rigzone|accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref>

Like most North Sea fields operated by [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]], it is named after a bird - in this case [[Common Goldeneye|''Bucephala clangula'']], a small duck found in Scotland and elsewhere.

