{{Infobox power transmission line | name = Tororo–Opuyo–Lira High Voltage Power Line | photo = | caption = | map = | country = [[Uganda]] | state = | province = | coordinates = {{coord|01|40|39|N|33|40|37|E|type:landmark_region:UG|display=inline}} | direction = South to North | start = [[Tororo]], [[Uganda]] | through = [[Mbale]], Opuyo, [[Dokolo]] | finish = [[Lira, Uganda]] | par = | owner = [[Government of Uganda]] | partners = [[African Development Bank]] | operator = [[Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited]] | cable_manufacturer = | cable_installer = | cable_layer = | substation_manufacturer = | substation_installer = | contractors = | construction = 2013 | expected = 2017 | est = | decom = | type = | current_type = AC | length =264 | length_mi = | tower_no = | capacity = | AC_voltage = 132kV | DC_voltage = | poles_no = | circuits_no = 2 }}
The '''Tororo–Opuyo–Lira High Voltage Power Line''' is a [[high voltage]] electricity power line, connecting the high voltage [[Electrical substation|substation]] at [[Tororo]], to another high voltage substation at [[Lira, Uganda |Lira]], in [[Uganda]].<ref name="One">{{cite web| date=29 January 2014 |url=http://www.uetcl.com/index.php/site-administrator/2014-01-29-09-43-25 |accessdate=3 January 2018 |location=Kampala | publisher=[[Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited]] (UETCL) | author=UETCL | title=Projects Under Implementation}}</ref>
==Location== The 132kV power line, begins at the 132kV substation at [[Tororo]], in [[Tororo District]], in the [[Eastern Region, Uganda|Eastern Region]] of Uganda. The line travels in a northerly direction through [[Mbale]], to the [[Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited]] high voltage substation at Opuyo, outside of [[Soroti]], in [[Soroti District]]. From there, it takes a general north-westerly course, through [[Dokolo District]], to end at [[Lira, Uganda|Lira]], in [[Lira District]], in the [[Northern Region, Uganda|Northern Region]] of Uganda, a total distance of approximately {{convert|264|km|0}}.<ref name="One"/>
==Overview== The power line is the major electricity conduit to the Eastern Region of Uganda, with extension to Northern Uganda. It is a 132 kilo-Volt, double-circuit installation, that harnesses power from the hydroelectric power stations on the [[Victoria Nile]] and the thermal and solar power plants in Tororo and Soroti, for onward transmission to the east and north of country.<ref name="Two">{{cite web| accessdate=3 January 2018 |first=Mudangha | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Rehabilitation-of--Tororo-Lira-power-transmission-lines-start/688334-1753716-lxua9fz/index.html |title=Rehabilitation of Tororo-Lira power transmission lines start | last=Kolyangha | date=21 April 2013 | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |location=Kampala}}</ref>
==Construction== Prior to 2013, the power line was primarily constructed of wooden poles, which were vulnerable to lightning, wild fires and termite damage. In 2013, the [[government of Uganda]], using money borrowed from the [[African Development Bank]], began replacing the wooden poles with metal structures. The main objective is to improve the availability, quality and reliability of power supply.<ref name="One"/><ref name="Two"/> [http://kalpatarupower.com/ Kalpataru Power Transmission Limited] (KPTL), based in [[India]], is the main contractor on this project. The engineering supervisor is ''Hifab Oy'' of [[Finland]].<ref name="One"/><ref name="Two"/> Construction stated in 2013,<ref name="Two"/> with completion expected in 2017.<ref name="One"/>
